built this project to understand how machine learning works in real drug discovery using chembl bioactivity data.
main goal was to predict pIC50 values for aromatase inhibitors by creating a full pipeline from data cleaning to 
feature engineering and model training.
model shows good performance with r2 score of 0.528 and rmse around 1.11 which means predictions are reasonably close to actual values. 
using 181 molecular fingerprint features helped capture important chemical patterns and model is clearly learning because predicted vs actual plot 
shows strong upward trend especially in pIC50 range 5 to 8 where most drug compounds exist.
one limitation is model struggles with very low potency compounds and some outliers where prediction is not accurate but this is normal in real 
drug discovery because of complex and diverse molecular structures.
overall this project shows complete workflow from raw chembl data to machine learning prediction and helped me understand how molecular fingerprints
and feature selection impact model performance. further improvement can be done by testing different models or applying this pipeline to other biological targets.
